252
00:11:17,727 --> 00:11:22,053
- [Narrator] At 4:01 p.m.,
Air Florida Flight 90

253
00:11:22,053 --> 00:11:24,269
crashed into the 14th Street bridge.

254
00:11:24,269 --> 00:11:25,829
(propellers whirring)

255
00:11:25,829 --> 00:11:28,710
- We get down there and we
don't really have a method

256
00:11:28,710 --> 00:11:32,440
for dealing with that
kind of mass casualty.

257
00:11:32,440 --> 00:11:35,566
The radio systems didn't
function like they should,

258
00:11:35,566 --> 00:11:38,351
we didn't have any place
to deal with the bodies.

259
00:11:38,351 --> 00:11:41,322
(dramatic music)

260
00:11:41,322 --> 00:11:44,321
- [Narrator] Passerby Lenny
Skutnik dove into the water

261
00:11:44,321 --> 00:11:46,509
to help save a drowning woman.

262
00:11:46,509 --> 00:11:47,442
- [Reporter] We have just learned

263
00:11:47,442 --> 00:11:51,076
that that woman fighting to
survive in the icy Potomac

264
00:11:51,076 --> 00:11:53,638
was one of the stewardesses
on board the plane,

265
00:11:53,638 --> 00:11:55,917
her name Kelly Dunman.

266
00:11:55,917 --> 00:11:59,905
- He really symbolized I
think for a lot of people here

267
00:11:59,905 --> 00:12:02,091
that people wanted to help

268
00:12:02,091 --> 00:12:04,004
and were willing to help each other.

269
00:12:04,004 --> 00:12:05,978
(dramatic music)

270
00:12:05,978 --> 00:12:07,773
- [Narrator] 74 people on the plane

271
00:12:07,773 --> 00:12:10,575
and four on the bridge were killed.

272
00:12:10,575 --> 00:12:14,521
- One of my dearest
friends was on that plane.

273
00:12:14,521 --> 00:12:17,998
She was the mother of
three young children.

274
00:12:17,998 --> 00:12:20,610
I miss her to this day.
(sirens wailing)

275
00:12:20,610 --> 00:12:22,141
- [Narrator] As word of the crash spread

276
00:12:22,141 --> 00:12:25,135
and the Washington Press
corps descended on the scene,

277
00:12:25,135 --> 00:12:29,984
it became clear that another
tragedy had struck the region.

278
00:12:29,984 --> 00:12:31,719
- Reporters couldn't get there

279
00:12:31,719 --> 00:12:34,727
because the Metro train also had derailed.

280
00:12:34,727 --> 00:12:37,107
- [Narrator] 30 minutes
after the plane crash

281
00:12:37,107 --> 00:12:40,237
an Orange Line train jumped
the tracks in a tunnel,

282
00:12:40,237 --> 00:12:42,001
near Federal Triangle.

283
00:12:42,001 --> 00:12:43,043
- [Reporter] Two women and a man

284
00:12:43,043 --> 00:12:45,551
whose names have not been
released were killed.

285
00:12:45,551 --> 00:12:49,708
- That forced the region
to think oh my goodness,

286
00:12:49,708 --> 00:12:51,125
what do we do if?

287
00:12:54,643 --> 00:12:55,498
- So for some many of our--

288
00:12:55,498 --> 00:12:58,259
- [Narrator] By 1982,
Barry's first term as mayor

289
00:12:58,259 --> 00:12:59,992
was coming to a close.

290
00:12:59,992 --> 00:13:03,153
For the first time since
his election in 1978,

291
00:13:03,153 --> 00:13:06,086
voters were given the
chance to judge his record.

292
00:13:06,086 --> 00:13:09,253
(funky, upbeat music)

293
00:13:10,790 --> 00:13:12,260
- He was elected by whites.

294
00:13:12,260 --> 00:13:13,752
As he won essentially

295
00:13:13,752 --> 00:13:14,906
with the votes of people
(people singing)

296
00:13:14,906 --> 00:13:16,953
in wards one, three, two, and six.

297
00:13:16,953 --> 00:13:18,120
- And this is just the beginning

298
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:19,576
of what we're going to do here.

299
00:13:19,576 --> 00:13:20,870
- [Narrator] But once in power,

300
00:13:20,870 --> 00:13:23,588
Barry knew that tying his political future

301
00:13:23,588 --> 00:13:27,044
to the city's white
residents was unsustainable.

302
00:13:27,044 --> 00:13:30,602
- He made an incredibly
prudent political decision

303
00:13:30,602 --> 00:13:33,439
to switch his base to black,

304
00:13:33,439 --> 00:13:36,516
through minority contracting programs

305
00:13:36,516 --> 00:13:37,710
and bringing black folks

306
00:13:37,710 --> 00:13:41,472
into key positions in the government.

307
00:13:41,472 --> 00:13:44,726
- I can remember him saying, "Listen.

308
00:13:44,726 --> 00:13:47,058
"You're gonna be able to advance,

309
00:13:47,058 --> 00:13:49,587
"you got to get prepared for leadership,"

310
00:13:49,587 --> 00:13:52,056
and for somebody like me,

311
00:13:52,056 --> 00:13:55,195
I got to be chief because of Barry.

312
00:13:55,195 --> 00:13:57,127
- [Narrator] Barry used
the power of his position

313
00:13:57,127 --> 00:13:59,961
to encourage the creation and development

314
00:13:59,961 --> 00:14:01,750
of African American owned businesses.

315
00:14:01,750 --> 00:14:03,327
♪ We found the proper place ♪

316
00:14:03,327 --> 00:14:05,696
- And if you're gonna do business in D.C.,

317
00:14:05,696 --> 00:14:07,743
one of the first questions they'd ask you,

318
00:14:07,743 --> 00:14:11,282
do you have minority
participation in this deal?

319
00:14:11,282 --> 00:14:14,365
What came about was a philosophy that

320
00:14:15,398 --> 00:14:17,739
white business should partner up

321
00:14:17,739 --> 00:14:20,586
with qualified African
American business people

322
00:14:20,586 --> 00:14:22,317
and once you get a black city council

323
00:14:22,317 --> 00:14:24,428
all of a sudden the white
law firms start saying

324
00:14:24,428 --> 00:14:25,993
we're gonna have black partners,

325
00:14:25,993 --> 00:14:27,547
and some of the white
businesses start saying

326
00:14:27,547 --> 00:14:29,941
we have to have black lobbyists.

327
00:14:29,941 --> 00:14:31,537
- [Narrator] The increased flow of money

328
00:14:31,537 --> 00:14:33,595
moving through the city's economy

329
00:14:33,595 --> 00:14:35,642
swelled the district's coffers,

330
00:14:35,642 --> 00:14:38,235
giving Barry the income
to spend on projects

331
00:14:38,235 --> 00:14:41,365
that benefited the city's poorer youth

332
00:14:41,365 --> 00:14:45,867
and build a base for the
rest of his political career.

333
00:14:45,867 --> 00:14:49,498
- My most memorable program
is the summer job program.

334
00:14:49,498 --> 00:14:52,128
Over a hundred thousand young people

335
00:14:52,128 --> 00:14:54,218
went through our summer job program.

336
00:14:54,218 --> 00:14:55,288
- I was just at some event

337
00:14:55,288 --> 00:14:58,551
and the guy who was in charge
of the people parking the cars

338
00:14:58,551 --> 00:15:00,758
came up to me, he says,
"I got my first job

339
00:15:00,758 --> 00:15:02,710
"in the Marion Barry summer job program."

340
00:15:02,710 --> 00:15:04,886
He said, "Now I help to run this company."

341
00:15:04,886 --> 00:15:06,750
- That was the bomb.

342
00:15:06,750 --> 00:15:09,525
You go down 500 C Street and
there's a long line of kids

343
00:15:09,525 --> 00:15:11,867
waitin' in line to get
their checks, you know.

344
00:15:11,867 --> 00:15:14,382
You would see them all downtown

345
00:15:14,382 --> 00:15:16,860
at The Go-Go at night. (laughing)

346
00:15:16,860 --> 00:15:19,520
So, that was awesome, yes indeed.

347
00:15:19,520 --> 00:15:21,765
- [Narrator] Recognizing
that the district's aging

348
00:15:21,765 --> 00:15:25,565
were underserved, Barry
also invested heavily

349
00:15:25,565 --> 00:15:27,897
in services for the elderly.

350
00:15:27,897 --> 00:15:29,366
- And the flip side of that for Barry was

351
00:15:29,366 --> 00:15:31,375
in addition to that being a good thing,

352
00:15:31,375 --> 00:15:34,244
was that he would take
buses, recreation buses,

353
00:15:34,244 --> 00:15:36,370
and take them all down to vote.

354
00:15:36,370 --> 00:15:39,214
(crowd chanting)

355
00:15:39,214 --> 00:15:40,307
- [Narrator] In 1982,

356
00:15:40,307 --> 00:15:42,827
Barry was elected to a
second term as mayor,

357
00:15:42,827 --> 00:15:45,243
with 81% of the vote.

358
00:15:45,243 --> 00:15:48,405
- I want to thank all
of you for reaffirming

359
00:15:48,405 --> 00:15:49,822
your faith in me.

360
00:15:51,319 --> 00:15:52,415
(audience cheering)

361
00:15:52,415 --> 00:15:56,424
- It was clear that his
success in the election

362
00:15:56,424 --> 00:15:58,372
had been largely through black folks

363
00:15:58,372 --> 00:16:00,869
and not from the white community.

364
00:16:00,869 --> 00:16:02,393
He said get over it.

365
00:16:02,393 --> 00:16:04,976
(upbeat music)

366
00:16:05,879 --> 00:16:06,918
- [Narrator] During his first term,

367
00:16:06,918 --> 00:16:10,121
Barry had honored promises
made to the gay community,

368
00:16:10,121 --> 00:16:13,671
a core constituency that
helped to elect him.

369
00:16:13,671 --> 00:16:16,337
- [Man] He understood that
we were a political power.

370
00:16:16,337 --> 00:16:19,120
- Just his willingness to say I will have

371
00:16:19,120 --> 00:16:21,998
openly gay people in my administration.

372
00:16:21,998 --> 00:16:25,229
Nobody did that at that
time, so that was huge.

373
00:16:25,229 --> 00:16:27,928
(upbeat music)

374
00:16:27,928 --> 00:16:30,429
- [Narrator] Barry's actions
helped to establish D.C.

375
00:16:30,429 --> 00:16:33,663
as one of the country's
most gay-friendly cities.

376
00:16:33,663 --> 00:16:35,695
- It affected most gay
people's social lives

377
00:16:35,695 --> 00:16:37,795
in that they became more open.

378
00:16:37,795 --> 00:16:42,066
- [Woman] It gave the
community this enormous number

379
00:16:42,066 --> 00:16:45,399
of healthy, happy ways of meeting people

380
00:16:46,290 --> 00:16:49,707
and so it made it a lot
easier for people to come out.

381
00:16:49,707 --> 00:16:53,671
("L'Amour" by Erasure)

382
00:16:53,671 --> 00:16:54,951
- [Narrator] By 1984,

383
00:16:54,951 --> 00:16:58,299
expansion of D.C.'s annual gay pride day

384
00:16:58,299 --> 00:17:00,915
to a week-long festival was complete,

385
00:17:00,915 --> 00:17:02,438
cementing Washington's status

386
00:17:02,438 --> 00:17:04,580
as home to one of the country's largest

387
00:17:04,580 --> 00:17:08,066
and most vibrant gay communities.

388
00:17:08,066 --> 00:17:11,233
(background cheering)

389
00:17:12,339 --> 00:17:14,134
Improvement in the city's fortunes

390
00:17:14,134 --> 00:17:16,275
also spread to the football field.

391
00:17:16,275 --> 00:17:19,198
("Thriller" by Michael Jackson)

392
00:17:19,198 --> 00:17:24,005
In 1981, team owner Jack Kent
Cooke fired coach Jack Pardee

393
00:17:24,005 --> 00:17:24,838
and replaced him

394
00:17:24,838 --> 00:17:29,193
with San Diego offensive
coordinator, Joe Gibbs.

395
00:17:29,193 --> 00:17:31,692
- At first I said if I'm not successful

396
00:17:31,692 --> 00:17:33,393
hey, that's part of life,

397
00:17:33,393 --> 00:17:34,806
but when I got there what I realized

398
00:17:34,806 --> 00:17:37,261
is just how many people depend on you.

399
00:17:37,261 --> 00:17:40,056
- [Narrator] The team
began the season 0-5.

400
00:17:40,056 --> 00:17:41,274
- I thought I was gonna be first guy

401
00:17:41,274 --> 00:17:45,547
to ever coach in the NFL
and never win a game,

402
00:17:45,547 --> 00:17:47,099
tell Pat please sell the dog,

403
00:17:47,099 --> 00:17:48,655
I'd hate to come home and see that fella

404
00:17:48,655 --> 00:17:51,637
draped over the steps. (laughing)

405
00:17:51,637 --> 00:17:54,031
- [Narrator] But a third of
the way through the '81 season,

406
00:17:54,031 --> 00:17:58,031
wins replaced losses, and
the team finished 8-8.

407
00:17:59,407 --> 00:18:01,980
- They had a really unique squad.

408
00:18:01,980 --> 00:18:05,275
Theismann was just really slick.

409
00:18:05,275 --> 00:18:07,051
- Hit.
- Joe T. was probably

410
00:18:07,051 --> 00:18:10,327
one of the most passionate
football players,

411
00:18:10,327 --> 00:18:13,003
I mean that guy wanted to be successful.

412
00:18:13,003 --> 00:18:13,836
(crowd cheering)

413
00:18:13,836 --> 00:18:15,819
- [Man] Riggins was a bull.

414
00:18:15,819 --> 00:18:17,919
I mean you had Joe Washington

415
00:18:17,919 --> 00:18:21,570
who was just this small, speedy guy.

416
00:18:21,570 --> 00:18:24,669
Art Monk, anything you
threw up, he caught.

417
00:18:24,669 --> 00:18:26,319
- Their hearts were big and fat,

418
00:18:26,319 --> 00:18:30,841
and they put a lot of
meat against that line.

419
00:18:30,841 --> 00:18:32,555
- [Crowd] We want Grant!

420
00:18:32,555 --> 00:18:34,212
We want Grant!

421
00:18:34,212 --> 00:18:35,713
We want Grant!

422
00:18:35,713 --> 00:18:36,858
- [Narrator] After going 8-1

423
00:18:36,858 --> 00:18:38,664
and first in the NFC East

424
00:18:38,664 --> 00:18:41,602
in the strike-shortened 1982 season,

425
00:18:41,602 --> 00:18:43,830
they hosted the NFC championship game

426
00:18:43,830 --> 00:18:46,786
against their fiercest rival.

427
00:18:46,786 --> 00:18:49,894
- The excitement at RFK you
heard outside the stadium,

428
00:18:49,894 --> 00:18:51,479
just up in the neighborhood

429
00:18:51,479 --> 00:18:53,873
you'd just hear that roaring crowd.

430
00:18:53,873 --> 00:18:54,881
(crowd cheering)

431
00:18:54,881 --> 00:18:57,569
- [Narrator] The home
team was leading 24-17

432
00:18:57,569 --> 00:18:59,901
with less than seven minutes remaining.

433
00:18:59,901 --> 00:19:01,601
- [Announcer] Play action fake to Dorsett,

434
00:19:01,601 --> 00:19:03,418
screen path, batted in the air by Lanley.

435
00:19:03,418 --> 00:19:05,969
Darryl Grant's there picks it off.

436
00:19:05,969 --> 00:19:08,111
Touchdown, Washington Redskins.

437
00:19:08,111 --> 00:19:09,234
Unbelievable!

438
00:19:09,234 --> 00:19:11,229
- [Man] The stadium was rocked.

439
00:19:11,229 --> 00:19:12,647
It was thunderous.

440
00:19:12,647 --> 00:19:14,117
- [Announcer] I do not believe it!

441
00:19:14,117 --> 00:19:15,903
(crowd roaring)

442
00:19:15,903 --> 00:19:18,348
- [Narrator] With that win,
the team headed to Pasadena

443
00:19:18,348 --> 00:19:22,008
to play the Miami Dolphins
in Superbowl XVII.

444
00:19:22,008 --> 00:19:25,223
(football players chanting)

445
00:19:25,223 --> 00:19:27,292
The game was close throughout.

446
00:19:27,292 --> 00:19:29,458
- It came down to the 4th quarter,

447
00:19:29,458 --> 00:19:31,377
I think we were on the plus 41 yard line,

448
00:19:31,377 --> 00:19:36,377
and it was 4th and one, and
I made a call to go for it.

449
00:19:36,440 --> 00:19:38,579
- [Announcer] There goes
(drowned out by music).

450
00:19:38,579 --> 00:19:39,887
Their touchdown surprised them.

451
00:19:39,887 --> 00:19:40,998
Hand to Riggins.

452
00:19:40,998 --> 00:19:43,770
He's got a good hold, he's
got the first down for 40.

453
00:19:43,770 --> 00:19:44,843
He's gone!

454
00:19:44,843 --> 00:19:47,676
The 35, the 30, the 20, he's gone!

455
00:19:48,612 --> 00:19:49,859
He's gone!

456
00:19:49,859 --> 00:19:52,543
Touchdown, Washington Redskins.

457
00:19:52,543 --> 00:19:55,457
Holy cow, was that a play or what!

458
00:19:55,457 --> 00:19:57,643
(crowd cheering)

459
00:19:57,643 --> 00:20:02,277
- [Narrator] The final
score, 27-17, Washington.

460
00:20:02,277 --> 00:20:04,579
- Redskins are number one!

461
00:20:04,579 --> 00:20:07,172
- Everybody poured into the streets

462
00:20:07,172 --> 00:20:09,619
of M Street in Georgetown.

463
00:20:09,619 --> 00:20:11,040
It was euphoric.

464
00:20:11,040 --> 00:20:14,550
The city's team finally
brought home the bacon.

465
00:20:14,550 --> 00:20:18,011
(woman shrieking)

466
00:20:18,011 --> 00:20:20,059
♪ Pump pump pump pump me up ♪

467
00:20:20,059 --> 00:20:21,717
(funky music)

468
00:20:21,717 --> 00:20:23,123
- [Narrator] Football
wasn't the only thing

469
00:20:23,123 --> 00:20:25,206
making fans at RFK cheer.

470
00:20:26,174 --> 00:20:28,908
- The Back To School Boogie,
the battle of the bands,

471
00:20:28,908 --> 00:20:30,379
you'd get an opportunity

472
00:20:30,379 --> 00:20:32,669
to see all these go-go bands perform

473
00:20:32,669 --> 00:20:34,950
inside of a huge stadium.

474
00:20:34,950 --> 00:20:36,439
♪ Come out here with family ♪

475
00:20:36,439 --> 00:20:39,038
- And I used to always say
if you can't move to go-go,

476
00:20:39,038 --> 00:20:40,844
you weren't meant to move.

477
00:20:40,844 --> 00:20:43,069
- I remember first time
hearing Trouble Funk,

478
00:20:43,069 --> 00:20:44,498
there's a song, Pump Me Up.

479
00:20:44,498 --> 00:20:46,422
♪ Pump pump pump pump me up ♪

480
00:20:46,422 --> 00:20:47,659
♪ Like the man with the super S ♪

481
00:20:47,659 --> 00:20:50,512
And Henry Rollins, he was my best friend,

482
00:20:50,512 --> 00:20:51,345
we heard it on the radio

483
00:20:51,345 --> 00:20:54,850
and we just pulled the car
over to listen to the song.

484
00:20:54,850 --> 00:20:56,310
♪ From the East to West ♪

485
00:20:56,310 --> 00:20:59,013
- [Narrator] In addition to
Chuck Brown and Trouble Funk,

486
00:20:59,013 --> 00:21:01,606
bands such as Rare Essence and E.U.

487
00:21:01,606 --> 00:21:05,932
created a music and culture
proud of its D.C. roots.

488
00:21:05,932 --> 00:21:08,334
- Look what I brought to y'all, all right?

489
00:21:08,334 --> 00:21:11,044
- Go-go was a product of a time

490
00:21:11,044 --> 00:21:15,127
when D.C. public schools
had more music programs.

491
00:21:16,978 --> 00:21:21,197
- Kids couldn't afford to buy instruments

492
00:21:21,197 --> 00:21:24,832
and so the kids would
check out their instruments

493
00:21:24,832 --> 00:21:26,452
and they'd go home to practice all right,

494
00:21:26,452 --> 00:21:28,893
but with the local go-go band.

495
00:21:28,893 --> 00:21:31,592
- [Narrator] Live recordings,
better known as PA tapes,

496
00:21:31,592 --> 00:21:35,310
became a form of currency for go-go fans.

497
00:21:35,310 --> 00:21:38,460
- We used to go to the go-gos
with our big boom boxes

498
00:21:38,460 --> 00:21:42,198
and stand in front of the speakers.

499
00:21:42,198 --> 00:21:44,234
- It was and still is a big thing

500
00:21:44,234 --> 00:21:45,854
to get your name called out,

501
00:21:45,854 --> 00:21:47,038
especially if your name is

502
00:21:47,038 --> 00:21:49,321
always heard on the PA tapes, you know.

503
00:21:49,321 --> 00:21:51,349
- Woo, that was a big feeling

504
00:21:51,349 --> 00:21:55,160
and so you wanted that
PA tape from this date.

505
00:21:55,160 --> 00:21:57,660
(funky music)

506
00:22:01,597 --> 00:22:04,590
- [Narrator] The City's
insatiable appetite for live go-go

507
00:22:04,590 --> 00:22:07,950
led to performances
springing up all over town.

508
00:22:07,950 --> 00:22:10,482
(funky music)

509
00:22:10,482 --> 00:22:12,558
- Everybody represented
where they came from.

510
00:22:12,558 --> 00:22:14,396
Junk Yard from Barry Farm,

511
00:22:14,396 --> 00:22:17,526
Pat Worth named himself after the area.

512
00:22:17,526 --> 00:22:22,334
- My first ever experience
playing live with a go-go band

513
00:22:22,334 --> 00:22:24,686
was in my friend's backyard

514
00:22:24,686 --> 00:22:27,628
and people would crowd
around and listen to us.

515
00:22:27,628 --> 00:22:29,568
- [Narrator] A compulsion
to play live music

516
00:22:29,568 --> 00:22:32,917
that lead to an unlikely
sharing of stages.

517
00:22:32,917 --> 00:22:36,078
- A lot of the regular
clubs like The Bayou

518
00:22:36,078 --> 00:22:39,824
and Desperados only booked big rock bands

519
00:22:39,824 --> 00:22:42,834
or big-named people, so
we would play anywhere

520
00:22:42,834 --> 00:22:45,480
and it would end up that
we would play together.

521
00:22:45,480 --> 00:22:50,480
("Should I Stay or Should
I Go" by The Clash)

522
00:22:53,075 --> 00:22:54,568
- [Narrator] One of these crossover venues

523
00:22:54,568 --> 00:22:57,191
was at 930 F Street, Northwest.

524
00:22:57,191 --> 00:23:00,615
- Their slogan was a place and a time.

525
00:23:00,615 --> 00:23:01,864
- [Narrator] When original owners

526
00:23:01,864 --> 00:23:03,742
Dody DiSanto and Jon Bowers

527
00:23:03,742 --> 00:23:08,091
opened The 930 Club in 1980,
their choice of location

528
00:23:08,091 --> 00:23:11,932
in the heart of downtown
was unconventional.

529
00:23:11,932 --> 00:23:13,801
- [Man] When the 930 was
there, there were peep shows

530
00:23:13,801 --> 00:23:17,551
and you know, liquor
stores and strip joints.

531
00:23:18,695 --> 00:23:21,458
People couldn't afford to
buy expensive real estate

532
00:23:21,458 --> 00:23:25,490
so they had to do it in
the bad parts of town.

533
00:23:25,490 --> 00:23:27,347
- [Narrator] The tiny odd-shaped space

534
00:23:27,347 --> 00:23:29,564
was an acquired taste.

535
00:23:29,564 --> 00:23:32,210
- There was really not
much room for the audience.

536
00:23:32,210 --> 00:23:34,191
It was like you were in a lobby.

537
00:23:34,191 --> 00:23:39,191
We would have bands show up
who were appalled and ask--

538
00:23:39,381 --> 00:23:41,817
♪ Should I stay or should I go ♪

539
00:23:41,817 --> 00:23:44,001
So where's the club?

540
00:23:44,001 --> 00:23:46,772
And some bands walked out.

541
00:23:46,772 --> 00:23:51,676
DJ Jazzy Jeff and the Fresh
Prince, Will Smith, walked out,

542
00:23:51,676 --> 00:23:53,482
two sold-out shows.

543
00:23:53,482 --> 00:23:55,445
(rock music)

544
00:23:55,445 --> 00:23:57,289
Course when the band did go on,

545
00:23:57,289 --> 00:23:59,788
you were right in front of them.

546
00:23:59,788 --> 00:24:01,742
(rock music)

547
00:24:01,742 --> 00:24:05,094
There was no closer
experience to see a show

548
00:24:05,094 --> 00:24:07,110
than the old 930 club.

549
00:24:07,110 --> 00:24:08,107
(rock music)

550
00:24:08,107 --> 00:24:09,628
- [Narrator] A unique venue
that became a favorite

551
00:24:09,628 --> 00:24:12,431
of the local hardcore punk scene,

552
00:24:12,431 --> 00:24:14,321
defined by its inclusion of anyone

553
00:24:14,321 --> 00:24:16,859
who didn't feel they belonged.

554
00:24:16,859 --> 00:24:17,726
- If you grew up in this town

555
00:24:17,726 --> 00:24:19,468
I think you feel really marginalized

556
00:24:19,468 --> 00:24:21,515
from one reason or another.

557
00:24:21,515 --> 00:24:23,362
- [Narrator] D.C. punk
gave birth to bands like

558
00:24:23,362 --> 00:24:25,558
Government Issue, State of Alert,

559
00:24:25,558 --> 00:24:29,380
and Minor Threat with Ian
MacKaye on lead vocals.

560
00:24:29,380 --> 00:24:32,762
(punk rock singing)

561
00:24:32,762 --> 00:24:35,344
- We identify as Washington D.C.

562
00:24:35,344 --> 00:24:37,612
It was a chip on our shoulder.

563
00:24:37,612 --> 00:24:38,642
- [Narrator] The region also produced

564
00:24:38,642 --> 00:24:41,235
the groundbreaking Bad Brains.

565
00:24:41,235 --> 00:24:44,235
(punk rock singing)

566
00:24:45,455 --> 00:24:48,302
- Bad Brains were four guys
from Anacostia in PG County

567
00:24:48,302 --> 00:24:51,469
and they were just an incredible band.

568
00:24:52,595 --> 00:24:54,465
(punk rock music)
- Yeah!

569
00:24:54,465 --> 00:24:58,987
♪ They're playing basketball ♪

570
00:24:58,987 --> 00:25:00,102
♪ We love that basket ♪

571
00:25:00,102 --> 00:25:01,529
[Narrator] The early '80s saw an explosion

572
00:25:01,529 --> 00:25:04,259
of the popularity of Georgetown
University basketball.

573
00:25:04,259 --> 00:25:08,017
♪ Playing basketball ♪

574
00:25:08,017 --> 00:25:11,294
- I can remember when Georgetown was just

575
00:25:11,294 --> 00:25:14,127
a type of ivy league Jesuit school

576
00:25:15,578 --> 00:25:19,075
but then John Thompson
came and turned it around

577
00:25:19,075 --> 00:25:22,254
and everyone was Hoyas, Hoyas, Hoyas.

578
00:25:22,254 --> 00:25:24,125
♪ Playing basketball ♪

579
00:25:24,125 --> 00:25:26,551
- [Narrator] The team's
tough defense-minded style

580
00:25:26,551 --> 00:25:30,218
helped to attract a
strong, loyal following.

581
00:25:31,317 --> 00:25:34,770
- A predominantly black basketball team

582
00:25:34,770 --> 00:25:39,353
at a really good university,
that inspired a lot of us.

583
00:25:40,358 --> 00:25:42,144
We hung out in Georgetown,

584
00:25:42,144 --> 00:25:45,818
we wore Georgetown University sweatshirts.

585
00:25:45,818 --> 00:25:47,453
- It was like a party to me.

586
00:25:47,453 --> 00:25:52,453
It was the place to be, I mean. (laughing)

587
00:25:52,496 --> 00:25:55,329
The energy was all over the place.

588
00:25:56,360 --> 00:25:58,491
- [Narrator] In March of 1982, the Hoyas

589
00:25:58,491 --> 00:26:00,045
led by center Patrick Ewing

590
00:26:00,045 --> 00:26:03,295
advanced to the NCAA championship game.

591
00:26:04,362 --> 00:26:05,779
With less than 10 seconds left

592
00:26:05,779 --> 00:26:07,773
they had a chance to
take the winning shot.

593
00:26:07,773 --> 00:26:08,991
- [Announcer] Fred Brown with the ball,

594
00:26:08,991 --> 00:26:11,250
oh, throws it to the wrong guy.

595
00:26:11,250 --> 00:26:12,981
- [Man] I had to turn the TV off.

596
00:26:12,981 --> 00:26:16,005
I couldn't stand to watch anymore.

597
00:26:16,005 --> 00:26:16,962
- [Narrator] Two seasons later,

598
00:26:16,962 --> 00:26:18,773
the team went 34-3,

599
00:26:18,773 --> 00:26:21,251
winning the big east championship.

600
00:26:21,251 --> 00:26:22,226
(crowd cheering)

601
00:26:22,226 --> 00:26:25,197
♪ They're playing basketball ♪

602
00:26:25,197 --> 00:26:27,465
- [Narrator] They advanced
through the NCAA regional,

603
00:26:27,465 --> 00:26:31,552
the final four, to the
championship game against Houston.

604
00:26:31,552 --> 00:26:32,385
(ball clinks)

605
00:26:32,385 --> 00:26:34,743
♪ Basketball ♪

606
00:26:34,743 --> 00:26:38,870
- Michael Graham just goes
up and tomahawk dunks it,

607
00:26:38,870 --> 00:26:41,852
and he looks at Pat and
he just points at him

608
00:26:41,852 --> 00:26:44,772
just to let him know okay, we got this.

609
00:26:44,772 --> 00:26:48,308
(crowd cheering)

610
00:26:48,308 --> 00:26:50,221
- [Announcer] Georgetown wins the title,

611
00:26:50,221 --> 00:26:53,191
and Fred Brown gets the hug.

612
00:26:53,191 --> 00:26:55,188
♪ To the, to the hoop ♪

613
00:26:55,188 --> 00:26:56,037
- [Narrator] The Hoyas were

614
00:26:56,037 --> 00:26:58,884
welcomed back to Washington as champions,

615
00:26:58,884 --> 00:27:01,446
and Coach Thompson as a hero.

616
00:27:01,446 --> 00:27:03,271
- And I think all of us feel

617
00:27:03,271 --> 00:27:05,864
a great pride in what you've accomplished.

618
00:27:05,864 --> 00:27:09,751
("How Soon Is Now" by The Smiths)

619
00:27:09,751 --> 00:27:11,168
- [Narrator] As President
Reagan campaigned

620
00:27:11,168 --> 00:27:14,651
for reelection in 1984, Mitch Snyder,

621
00:27:14,651 --> 00:27:16,617
the leader of homeless advocacy group,

622
00:27:16,617 --> 00:27:20,826
Community For Creative
Non-Violence, or CCNV,

623
00:27:20,826 --> 00:27:23,065
staged a hunger strike to demand

624
00:27:23,065 --> 00:27:25,100
the administration renovate a shelter

625
00:27:25,100 --> 00:27:27,317
in an abandoned federal building.

626
00:27:27,317 --> 00:27:29,423
- The administration's
saying in everybody's name,

627
00:27:29,423 --> 00:27:32,587
including ours, that it
has no responsibility

628
00:27:32,587 --> 00:27:35,437
to people who are the poorest of the poor.

629
00:27:35,437 --> 00:27:39,604
("How Soon Is Now" by The Smiths)

630
00:27:41,855 --> 00:27:44,375
- My sister-in-law, for a very brief time,

631
00:27:44,375 --> 00:27:47,375
was in HUD dealing with the homeless

632
00:27:48,709 --> 00:27:52,061
and she wanted to go and
interview Mitch Snyder

633
00:27:52,061 --> 00:27:56,731
and essentially the
administration said don't do it,

634
00:27:56,731 --> 00:27:58,116
and don't do anything.

635
00:27:58,116 --> 00:28:03,116
♪ Needs to be loved, just
like everybody else does ♪

636
00:28:06,803 --> 00:28:11,515
- [Narrator] 51 days into his
protest, Snyder got his wish.

637
00:28:11,515 --> 00:28:14,142
- I think we capitulated to some degree.

638
00:28:14,142 --> 00:28:15,959
Truth be told, Reagan's a sensitive,

639
00:28:15,959 --> 00:28:18,834
I mean something like
that would affect him.

640
00:28:18,834 --> 00:28:19,991
- [Narrator] Two days later,

641
00:28:19,991 --> 00:28:22,404
President Ronald Reagan was reelected.

642
00:28:22,404 --> 00:28:24,083
- You ain't seen nothin' yet.

643
00:28:24,083 --> 00:28:27,318
(audience applauding)

644
00:28:27,318 --> 00:28:29,083
- I had several friends
that seemed to have

645
00:28:29,083 --> 00:28:31,279
this continual flu bug,

646
00:28:31,279 --> 00:28:34,671
and then it became pneumonia
and then they just died.

647
00:28:34,671 --> 00:28:37,328
- [Narrator] As Reagan
began his second term,

648
00:28:37,328 --> 00:28:40,321
a lack of action towards
those suffering and dying

649
00:28:40,321 --> 00:28:42,631
from HIV infection persisted.

650
00:28:42,631 --> 00:28:43,628
- [Reporter] White House officials confirm

651
00:28:43,628 --> 00:28:45,098
that the president has never talked

652
00:28:45,098 --> 00:28:48,668
with his surgeon general about AIDS.

653
00:28:48,668 --> 00:28:49,824
- [Narrator] Those in
the district turned to

654
00:28:49,824 --> 00:28:52,176
The Washington Blade for information.

655
00:28:52,176 --> 00:28:54,307
- The community desperately needed

656
00:28:54,307 --> 00:28:57,625
information about the disease.

657
00:28:57,625 --> 00:28:59,904
- [Narrator] On April 4th, 1983,

658
00:28:59,904 --> 00:29:01,844
the Whitman-Walker Clinic held D.C.'s

659
00:29:01,844 --> 00:29:04,765
first public forum on the epidemic.

660
00:29:04,765 --> 00:29:08,018
- Whitman Walker was one
of the founding fathers

661
00:29:08,018 --> 00:29:09,685
of AIDS information.

662
00:29:11,558 --> 00:29:13,992
But they also helped house people,

663
00:29:13,992 --> 00:29:15,914
they helped to feed people.

664
00:29:15,914 --> 00:29:17,972
They had to actually step
in and become involved

665
00:29:17,972 --> 00:29:19,828
in the link between the doctors

666
00:29:19,828 --> 00:29:21,837
and the hospitals and the patients

667
00:29:21,837 --> 00:29:22,980
because a lot of people were being

668
00:29:22,980 --> 00:29:24,180
turned away from hospitals.

669
00:29:24,180 --> 00:29:27,507
♪ Can you tell me why ♪

670
00:29:27,507 --> 00:29:31,118
♪ Can you tell me why ♪

671
00:29:31,118 --> 00:29:33,440
- [Narrator] But the deaths
of two public figures

672
00:29:33,440 --> 00:29:36,630
with ties to Washington
forced the country,

673
00:29:36,630 --> 00:29:39,373
and the president, to act.

674
00:29:39,373 --> 00:29:43,374
- Rock Hudson was familiar
with the president himself

675
00:29:43,374 --> 00:29:47,101
and an individual who had one, particular,

676
00:29:47,101 --> 00:29:50,934
very influential friend in Washington.

677
00:29:50,934 --> 00:29:52,939
Elizabeth Taylor.

678
00:29:52,939 --> 00:29:56,831
Not only was she an icon of the movies,

679
00:29:56,831 --> 00:30:01,328
she was also married to a
US senator from Virginia,

680
00:30:01,328 --> 00:30:02,913
John Warner.

681
00:30:02,913 --> 00:30:07,628
And so minds were changed and
the perception began to shift.

682
00:30:07,628 --> 00:30:12,628
- That science will continue
to find the critical answers.

683
00:30:13,287 --> 00:30:14,936
- Jerry Smith, my favorite tight end

684
00:30:14,936 --> 00:30:18,671
for the Washington Redskins,
then he was stricken with AIDS,

685
00:30:18,671 --> 00:30:22,338
it became apparent that
this He-Man was gay.

686
00:30:23,966 --> 00:30:26,013
- [Darian] Ronald Reagan's
opinion definitely changed

687
00:30:26,013 --> 00:30:27,851
because these were your friends dying.

688
00:30:27,851 --> 00:30:30,135
Same thing happened to me.

689
00:30:30,135 --> 00:30:32,218
- [Crowd] Gay rights now!

690
00:30:33,148 --> 00:30:34,398
Gay rights now!

691
00:30:36,247 --> 00:30:38,517
- [Narrator] A year after
Jerry Smith's passing,

692
00:30:38,517 --> 00:30:41,991
an estimated half million
people descended on Washington

693
00:30:41,991 --> 00:30:46,401
with a second march for
gay and lesbian rights.

694
00:30:46,401 --> 00:30:48,441
♪ Every bond you break ♪

695
00:30:48,441 --> 00:30:51,195
♪ Every step you take
I'll be watching you ♪

696
00:30:51,195 --> 00:30:53,444
- [Narrator] The highlight,
a massive memorial quilt

697
00:30:53,444 --> 00:30:55,320
covering the Mall with the names of the

698
00:30:55,320 --> 00:30:59,131
thousands of Americans
who had died of AIDS.

699
00:30:59,131 --> 00:31:00,261
♪ I'll be watching you ♪

700
00:31:00,261 --> 00:31:04,366
- America is a quilt,
made up of many patches,

701
00:31:04,366 --> 00:31:08,366
many pieces, many textures
where everybody fits.

702
00:31:09,994 --> 00:31:12,294
- Everyone who was there
just looked at each other

703
00:31:12,294 --> 00:31:16,105
and either cried or smiled
or a combination of the two.

704
00:31:16,105 --> 00:31:17,461
♪ I'll be watching you ♪

705
00:31:17,461 --> 00:31:19,212
♪ Every move you make ♪

706
00:31:19,212 --> 00:31:21,126
♪ Every vow you break ♪

707
00:31:21,126 --> 00:31:23,341
♪ Every smile you fake ♪

708
00:31:23,341 --> 00:31:27,373
("Road To Nowhere" by Talking Heads)

709
00:31:27,373 --> 00:31:30,468
- [Narrator] By 1987, the
decade's early promise

710
00:31:30,468 --> 00:31:32,013
was beginning to fade.

711
00:31:32,013 --> 00:31:36,140
♪ We're on a road to nowhere ♪

712
00:31:36,140 --> 00:31:38,890
♪ Come on inside ♪

713
00:31:40,782 --> 00:31:42,146
- [Narrator] Attempts to give the district

714
00:31:42,146 --> 00:31:46,753
congressional representation
and statehood had gone nowhere.

715
00:31:46,753 --> 00:31:49,927
Many started to ask if
Barry's management of the city

716
00:31:49,927 --> 00:31:51,806
was part of the problem.

717
00:31:51,806 --> 00:31:54,104
- Marion Barry was
already starting to have

718
00:31:54,104 --> 00:31:58,184
some budget problems,
running some deficits,

719
00:31:58,184 --> 00:32:01,244
but he didn't cut his crony contracts,

720
00:32:01,244 --> 00:32:04,100
he didn't cut waste fraud and abuse,

721
00:32:04,100 --> 00:32:07,267
what he cut was 1,500 police officers.

722
00:32:08,628 --> 00:32:13,125
- [Narrator] Mayor Barry's
lifestyle also raised questions.

723
00:32:13,125 --> 00:32:14,591
- [Reporter] Karen Johnson
just told authorities

724
00:32:14,591 --> 00:32:17,909
that she sold the mayor
cocaine, 20 to 30 times,

725
00:32:17,909 --> 00:32:20,650
from late 1980 to 1982.

726
00:32:20,650 --> 00:32:24,983
- [Man] He was notorious
for staying out late

727
00:32:24,983 --> 00:32:27,083
with women who were not his wife.

728
00:32:27,083 --> 00:32:29,932
This is when he would
use the security detail

729
00:32:29,932 --> 00:32:31,830
to procure women for him.

730
00:32:31,830 --> 00:32:33,951
- Marion Barry tonight angrily denied

731
00:32:33,951 --> 00:32:37,752
that he has been hospitalized
after overdosing on cocaine.

732
00:32:37,752 --> 00:32:41,835
- Marion Barry became too
comfortable with power.

733
00:32:42,700 --> 00:32:45,431
After winning over the
overwhelming majority

734
00:32:45,431 --> 00:32:47,708
of the African American population,

735
00:32:47,708 --> 00:32:50,875
he felt he could no longer be removed.

736
00:32:51,921 --> 00:32:52,929
- He was powerful,

737
00:32:52,929 --> 00:32:56,351
he could make a lot of
things happen in your ward.

738
00:32:56,351 --> 00:32:58,755
Hey, do you want that new fire station?

739
00:32:58,755 --> 00:33:00,772
Do you want the library?

740
00:33:00,772 --> 00:33:02,578
- [Narrator] Growing
discontent that led Barry

741
00:33:02,578 --> 00:33:07,103
to have real competition in
the '86 mayoral election.

742
00:33:07,103 --> 00:33:10,032
- In Washington D.C., where
the voter registration

743
00:33:10,032 --> 00:33:13,365
was 10 to one, Democrats to Republicans,

744
00:33:15,041 --> 00:33:17,208
I got a third of the vote.

745
00:33:18,381 --> 00:33:19,355
- [Narrator] Though Schwartz's tally

746
00:33:19,355 --> 00:33:21,268
exceeded everyone's expectations,

747
00:33:21,268 --> 00:33:23,914
Barry's base delivered him a third term,

748
00:33:23,914 --> 00:33:26,885
with 61% of the vote.

749
00:33:26,885 --> 00:33:29,898
- Washington Post endorsed
him three straight times,

750
00:33:29,898 --> 00:33:32,619
I think with growing reluctance
or something like that

751
00:33:32,619 --> 00:33:33,731
the third time.

752
00:33:33,731 --> 00:33:34,677
(background chattering)

753
00:33:34,677 --> 00:33:36,388
- [Narrator] But the
electorate and opinion pages

754
00:33:36,388 --> 00:33:38,947
cooling on Barry did nothing

755
00:33:38,947 --> 00:33:42,466
to slow his larger than life persona.

756
00:33:42,466 --> 00:33:46,319
- When people elected me,
they didn't elect me pope.

757
00:33:46,319 --> 00:33:48,400
They elected me mayor.

758
00:33:48,400 --> 00:33:51,234
I'd go out at night at nine
o'clock or ten o'clock,

759
00:33:51,234 --> 00:33:53,051
