00:44:59,912 --> 00:45:04,912
reportedly partying so hard
he was taken to the hospital.

1013
00:45:04,912 --> 00:45:07,569
Barry returned to D.C. the next day.

1014
00:45:07,569 --> 00:45:09,344
- It's unfortunate that so much snow fell,

1015
00:45:09,344 --> 00:45:11,475
which we certainly aren't responsible for.

1016
00:45:11,475 --> 00:45:12,808
(background chanting)

1017
00:45:12,808 --> 00:45:14,384
- [Narrator] Barry's lack of attention

1018
00:45:14,384 --> 00:45:16,358
was especially problematic,

1019
00:45:16,358 --> 00:45:20,136
as crack-related violence
threatened to overrun the city.

1020
00:45:20,136 --> 00:45:21,543
- The strange thing about it,

1021
00:45:21,543 --> 00:45:24,316
he never would tell you to do anything

1022
00:45:24,316 --> 00:45:27,056
except lock up the drug dealers.

1023
00:45:27,056 --> 00:45:28,518
- Outside of the killings,

1024
00:45:28,518 --> 00:45:32,212
one of the lowest crime
rates in the country.

1025
00:45:32,212 --> 00:45:33,045
- [Narrator] At the same time

1026
00:45:33,045 --> 00:45:35,809
the district's youth were
dragged into the epidemic,

1027
00:45:35,809 --> 00:45:39,160
the city cut funding for
recreational services,

1028
00:45:39,160 --> 00:45:42,887
leaving go-gos one of the few
places to meet and gather.

1029
00:45:42,887 --> 00:45:47,188
- One element of go-go
is call and response.

1030
00:45:47,188 --> 00:45:50,476
It's very easy for a lead talker

1031
00:45:50,476 --> 00:45:54,643
to ask a crowd is Southeast
better than Northeast,

1032
00:45:56,893 --> 00:46:00,226
and so there's this automatic tribalism.

1033
00:46:01,714 --> 00:46:05,547
A few go-go bands would
sort of advertise PCP.

1034
00:46:08,367 --> 00:46:09,996
Tell me now, what y'all smoke?

1035
00:46:09,996 --> 00:46:12,444
And the people would respond Love Boat.

1036
00:46:12,444 --> 00:46:15,426
- And you get a whole bunch
of kids together just to dance

1037
00:46:15,426 --> 00:46:17,716
and all that and somebody pulls out a gun.

1038
00:46:17,716 --> 00:46:19,810
- [Narrator] Go-go's rise
to national prominence

1039
00:46:19,810 --> 00:46:23,895
stalled as the music became
identified with violence.

1040
00:46:23,895 --> 00:46:26,773
- It was part of society.

1041
00:46:26,773 --> 00:46:29,751
Unfortunately, knuckleheads
like music too.

1042
00:46:29,751 --> 00:46:31,905
♪ I'm feeling like a bum now ♪

1043
00:46:31,905 --> 00:46:33,868
- [Narrator] Under the
name The Go Go Posse,

1044
00:46:33,868 --> 00:46:36,819
a number of local bands recorded a single

1045
00:46:36,819 --> 00:46:38,611
promoting an end to the violence,

1046
00:46:38,611 --> 00:46:42,172
called D.C. Don't Stand for Dodge City.

1047
00:46:42,172 --> 00:46:44,188
♪ Like the wild wild
west and its calamity ♪

1048
00:46:44,188 --> 00:46:47,036
♪ But D.C. don't mean Dodge City ♪

1049
00:46:47,036 --> 00:46:50,248
♪ D.C. don't mean Dodge City ♪

1050
00:46:50,248 --> 00:46:52,348
- Didn't change my life
because go-go music

1051
00:46:52,348 --> 00:46:55,478
oftentimes, it would
glorify all of the things

1052
00:46:55,478 --> 00:46:59,835
that this particular song
was speaking against.

1053
00:46:59,835 --> 00:47:01,767
- [Narrator] As the death toll mounted,

1054
00:47:01,767 --> 00:47:04,066
the city gained a dubious title.

1055
00:47:04,066 --> 00:47:05,281
- Washington is now called

1056
00:47:05,281 --> 00:47:07,384
the murder capital of the country.

1057
00:47:07,384 --> 00:47:08,359
(sirens wailing)

1058
00:47:08,359 --> 00:47:11,025
- My kids were in high school at the time

1059
00:47:11,025 --> 00:47:13,682
and they had on their wall

1060
00:47:13,682 --> 00:47:16,444
a list of the people who they knew,

1061
00:47:16,444 --> 00:47:21,412
either from their neighborhood
or their school who had died.

1062
00:47:21,412 --> 00:47:25,090
Before they graduated
from Dunbar High School,

1063
00:47:25,090 --> 00:47:27,840
that list had grown to 25 people.

1064
00:47:31,863 --> 00:47:34,005
- [Narrator] While crack created squalor

1065
00:47:34,005 --> 00:47:37,060
in previously vibrant
residential neighborhoods,

1066
00:47:37,060 --> 00:47:41,008
the city's commercial areas
were enjoying a relative boom.

1067
00:47:41,008 --> 00:47:42,675
- Downtown was dead.

1068
00:47:44,631 --> 00:47:48,338
And Barry said we gotta
do something about this.

1069
00:47:48,338 --> 00:47:50,471
Developers went to him
and said we want this,

1070
00:47:50,471 --> 00:47:55,143
we want that, and gave them
the land virtually free

1071
00:47:55,143 --> 00:47:57,718
and these projects were built.

1072
00:47:57,718 --> 00:47:59,515
- And we persuaded the banks and others

1073
00:47:59,515 --> 00:48:01,344
to lend money to these developers.

1074
00:48:01,344 --> 00:48:02,338
(upbeat music)

1075
00:48:02,338 --> 00:48:03,171
- [Narrator] After some politicking,

1076
00:48:03,171 --> 00:48:04,622
the Georgetown Waterfront

1077
00:48:04,622 --> 00:48:08,057
was one of the first
vistas to see results.

1078
00:48:08,057 --> 00:48:09,978
- Marion Barry recognized

1079
00:48:09,978 --> 00:48:14,839
that Washington Harbor could
be an enormous boom to the city

1080
00:48:14,839 --> 00:48:18,084
and so he was very instrumental.

1081
00:48:18,084 --> 00:48:19,890
- [Narrator] The success
of projects in Georgetown

1082
00:48:19,890 --> 00:48:22,313
and downtown gave Barry the confidence

1083
00:48:22,313 --> 00:48:24,983
to try to redevelop less likely locations

1084
00:48:24,983 --> 00:48:28,867
including ground zero of the '68 riots.

1085
00:48:28,867 --> 00:48:30,348
- If you told someone you were going to 14

1086
00:48:30,348 --> 00:48:33,089
they knew you were going
to buy drugs, period.

1087
00:48:33,089 --> 00:48:35,357
- [Narrator] The Frank D.
Reeves Municipal Center,

1088
00:48:35,357 --> 00:48:38,095
named after the lawyer and
local civil rights leader,

1089
00:48:38,095 --> 00:48:39,345
opened in 1986.

1090
00:48:40,543 --> 00:48:43,438
- People who were going to
work in those offices every day

1091
00:48:43,438 --> 00:48:45,510
would need services,

1092
00:48:45,510 --> 00:48:50,510
and even though at the time
it seemed fairly farfetched

1093
00:48:50,570 --> 00:48:53,971
there was a certain sense
that it would restore

1094
00:48:53,971 --> 00:48:58,964
an element of validity to a
once flourishing neighborhood.

1095
00:48:58,964 --> 00:49:00,244
(upbeat music)

1096
00:49:00,244 --> 00:49:02,585
- [Narrator] Several
long-closed icons of the past

1097
00:49:02,585 --> 00:49:04,592
were also resurrected.

1098
00:49:04,592 --> 00:49:06,164
The Old Post Office,

1099
00:49:06,164 --> 00:49:10,280
a Romanesque Revival
structure dating to 1899,

1100
00:49:10,280 --> 00:49:14,126
had been on the verge of
the wrecking ball for years.

1101
00:49:14,126 --> 00:49:15,815
- [Arthur] Sir David Wills,

1102
00:49:15,815 --> 00:49:19,365
who was heir to the
tobacco fortune in England,

1103
00:49:19,365 --> 00:49:23,416
cast a replica of the Westminster bells

1104
00:49:23,416 --> 00:49:26,819
as a bicentennial gift
to the United States.

1105
00:49:26,819 --> 00:49:28,605
He had this idea that they should hang

1106
00:49:28,605 --> 00:49:30,590
in the dome of the Capitol.

1107
00:49:30,590 --> 00:49:34,191
- [Narrator] But the Capitol
wasn't built for that purpose.

1108
00:49:34,191 --> 00:49:36,709
- One bong of these great bells

1109
00:49:36,709 --> 00:49:40,637
and the Capitol dome would be
sitting down over the Mall.

1110
00:49:40,637 --> 00:49:43,800
The congress was so concerned about it

1111
00:49:43,800 --> 00:49:47,682
that they appropriated
a new amount of money

1112
00:49:47,682 --> 00:49:51,906
and that was what finally
saved the entire building.

1113
00:49:51,906 --> 00:49:53,773
- All this was done with partnerships

1114
00:49:53,773 --> 00:49:57,282
and I think the results have been amazing.

1115
00:49:57,282 --> 00:49:59,088
- [Narrator] Saving Union Station,

1116
00:49:59,088 --> 00:50:01,039
a neglected Beaux-Art's masterpiece

1117
00:50:01,039 --> 00:50:04,380
that had become the city's
unofficial homeless shelter

1118
00:50:04,380 --> 00:50:07,939
became the responsibility of
a public private partnership.

1119
00:50:07,939 --> 00:50:09,725
- I thought it was very successful.

1120
00:50:09,725 --> 00:50:13,892
They were very careful in
preserving great spaces.

1121
00:50:14,854 --> 00:50:17,416
("Axel F" by Harold Faltermeyer)

1122
00:50:17,416 --> 00:50:21,145
(background chattering)
(dramatic music)

1123
00:50:21,145 --> 00:50:22,676
- [Narrator] D.C.'s downtown areas

1124
00:50:22,676 --> 00:50:24,703
received an additional boost

1125
00:50:24,703 --> 00:50:28,620
as a slew of local theaters
opened their doors.

1126
00:50:29,755 --> 00:50:32,328
- These little companies
started springing up

1127
00:50:32,328 --> 00:50:34,470
because downtown was so empty

1128
00:50:34,470 --> 00:50:37,032
that they could get space cheap.

1129
00:50:37,032 --> 00:50:39,709
The Wooly Mammoth and the Studio theaters

1130
00:50:39,709 --> 00:50:43,797
opened on 14th Street,
14th Street sort of became

1131
00:50:43,797 --> 00:50:46,630
the center of alternative theater.

1132
00:50:47,955 --> 00:50:50,780
- [Narrator] But at first,
residents weren't convinced.

1133
00:50:50,780 --> 00:50:55,000
- I would go over there to
watch some of their shows.

1134
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:59,167
10, 15, 20 people in the
audience plus the actors.

1135
00:51:00,835 --> 00:51:02,571
- [Narrator] But in
time, people's reluctance

1136
00:51:02,571 --> 00:51:04,660
to come downtown eased,

1137
00:51:04,660 --> 00:51:06,267
and Washington began its rise

1138
00:51:06,267 --> 00:51:09,322
to America's second city of theater.

1139
00:51:09,322 --> 00:51:10,688
- Washington was like that.

1140
00:51:10,688 --> 00:51:15,688
I mean, it had certain kinds
of cultural niches if you will.

1141
00:51:17,996 --> 00:51:22,497
- I'm a Washingtonian and
the first theater I ever saw

1142
00:51:22,497 --> 00:51:25,914
was from the top balcony of the National.

1143
00:51:26,816 --> 00:51:28,562
- [Narrator] As Washington's
theater scene gained

1144
00:51:28,562 --> 00:51:30,206
countrywide attention,

1145
00:51:30,206 --> 00:51:32,317
it established an award named in honor

1146
00:51:32,317 --> 00:51:34,837
of one of the city's
most acclaimed daughters

1147
00:51:34,837 --> 00:51:38,647
to recognize local theatrical excellence.

1148
00:51:38,647 --> 00:51:42,484
- The great Washington
Post critic, Richard Coe

1149
00:51:42,484 --> 00:51:46,246
called on his friendship with Helen Hayes

1150
00:51:46,246 --> 00:51:49,370
and together they created
the Helen Hayes Awards

1151
00:51:49,370 --> 00:51:52,436
and once the Helen Hayes Awards started,

1152
00:51:52,436 --> 00:51:55,269
more companies started popping up.

1153
00:51:56,322 --> 00:51:58,736
By the end of the decade,
Washington was on the

1154
00:51:58,736 --> 00:52:01,236
same playing field as Chicago.

1155
00:52:03,367 --> 00:52:05,562
- [Narrator] The region's
growing interest in the arts

1156
00:52:05,562 --> 00:52:08,334
was exploited by
Washington's TV affiliates,

1157
00:52:08,334 --> 00:52:10,385
still hungry for novel programming.

1158
00:52:10,385 --> 00:52:11,855
- The critics really-- (drowned
out by orchestral music)

1159
00:52:11,855 --> 00:52:14,711
- The king of the critics
in Washington D.C.

1160
00:52:14,711 --> 00:52:17,156
was Davey Marlin-Jones.

1161
00:52:17,156 --> 00:52:18,864
Davey was one of the
most interesting people

1162
00:52:18,864 --> 00:52:20,124
I had ever met.

1163
00:52:20,124 --> 00:52:22,171
- There may be something there.

1164
00:52:22,171 --> 00:52:23,671
- Davey wore hats.

1165
00:52:24,720 --> 00:52:27,516
He also pushed the
envelope with his clothes,

1166
00:52:27,516 --> 00:52:29,563
he pushed his envelope in every way.

1167
00:52:29,563 --> 00:52:30,643
- Tight.

1168
00:52:30,643 --> 00:52:31,609
Taut.

1169
00:52:31,609 --> 00:52:32,671
Tense.

1170
00:52:32,671 --> 00:52:34,423
- Davey owned this town.

1171
00:52:34,423 --> 00:52:37,806
- Inside the theater called life.

1172
00:52:37,806 --> 00:52:40,849
- [Narrator] A popular format
that encouraged imitation.

1173
00:52:40,849 --> 00:52:43,199
- Every station in town had a critic

1174
00:52:43,199 --> 00:52:46,550
and it was because we were all
trying to compete with Davey.

1175
00:52:46,550 --> 00:52:50,341
It was one of the great
gags of local television.

1176
00:52:50,341 --> 00:52:52,177
When he finished his report,

1177
00:52:52,177 --> 00:52:55,412
you didn't know if he liked
the movie or not. (chuckling)

1178
00:52:55,412 --> 00:52:59,822
- Hope you find one cinematic
sparkler among them.

1179
00:52:59,822 --> 00:53:01,849
Davey Marlin-Jones.

1180
00:53:01,849 --> 00:53:04,232
- I tried to make myself
different from Davey

1181
00:53:04,232 --> 00:53:07,308
so I used a ratings system.

1182
00:53:07,308 --> 00:53:10,362
On my scale of one to four stars,

1183
00:53:10,362 --> 00:53:12,571
Raiders of the Lost Ark gets a five.

1184
00:53:12,571 --> 00:53:14,259
So at least when I was finished

1185
00:53:14,259 --> 00:53:16,916
you would know what I
thought of the movie or not.

1186
00:53:16,916 --> 00:53:19,555
(upbeat music)
(crowd cheering)

1187
00:53:19,555 --> 00:53:22,411
- [Narrator] In 1986,
Washington's football team

1188
00:53:22,411 --> 00:53:25,252
picked up journeyman
quarterback Doug Williams

1189
00:53:25,252 --> 00:53:27,976
to back up its young
phenom, Jay Schroeder.

1190
00:53:27,976 --> 00:53:29,604
("Walk This Way" by RUN-DMC)

1191
00:53:29,604 --> 00:53:30,759
During the following season,

1192
00:53:30,759 --> 00:53:32,334
William shared quarterback duties

1193
00:53:32,334 --> 00:53:34,016
with the oft-injured Schroeder.

1194
00:53:34,016 --> 00:53:35,107
(players shouting)

1195
00:53:35,107 --> 00:53:37,418
But once the team made it to the playoffs,

1196
00:53:37,418 --> 00:53:41,974
Williams' performance put
an end to any controversy.

1197
00:53:41,974 --> 00:53:46,974
- We had to go to Chicago
playing 13 below temperatures.

1198
00:53:47,368 --> 00:53:48,739
We won.

1199
00:53:48,739 --> 00:53:52,489
("Walk This Way" by RUN-DMC)

1200
00:53:53,359 --> 00:53:56,323
The championship game against
the Minnesota Vikings,

1201
00:53:56,323 --> 00:53:58,274
I came off the bench and we won the game

1202
00:53:58,274 --> 00:54:00,688
and at coach's press conference,

1203
00:54:00,688 --> 00:54:03,767
he mentioned that I was gonna
be the starting quarterback,

1204
00:54:03,767 --> 00:54:06,225
me being the first African American

1205
00:54:06,225 --> 00:54:07,738
to play in the Superbowl.

1206
00:54:07,738 --> 00:54:09,196
I really cherished that time,

1207
00:54:09,196 --> 00:54:11,706
and for two weeks leading up to that game

1208
00:54:11,706 --> 00:54:13,789
it was pretty much crazy.

1209
00:54:15,203 --> 00:54:17,330
- [Narrator] The game started out badly.

1210
00:54:17,330 --> 00:54:19,534
- [Announcer] Touchdown, Denver, 56--

1211
00:54:19,534 --> 00:54:20,626
- The score was 10 to nothing

1212
00:54:20,626 --> 00:54:23,515
against the Redskins in the first quarter.

1213
00:54:23,515 --> 00:54:25,624
- [Narrator] And then, it got worse.

1214
00:54:25,624 --> 00:54:27,052
- I hyper-extended my knee,

1215
00:54:27,052 --> 00:54:29,205
didn't know it at that particular time

1216
00:54:29,205 --> 00:54:30,486
whether or not I was gonna be able

1217
00:54:30,486 --> 00:54:32,355
to finish the football game.

1218
00:54:32,355 --> 00:54:35,210
- I was gonna substitute
for him, he said hey,

1219
00:54:35,210 --> 00:54:38,862
get back out, I want
this, it's is my team.

1220
00:54:38,862 --> 00:54:39,700
(rock music)
- Touchdown!

1221
00:54:39,700 --> 00:54:42,052
- [Narrator] In a historic
reversal of fortune,

1222
00:54:42,052 --> 00:54:45,569
the team scored five touchdowns
in the second quarter.

1223
00:54:45,569 --> 00:54:46,482
- [Announcer] Touchdown!

1224
00:54:46,482 --> 00:54:48,550
Washington takes the lead!

1225
00:54:48,550 --> 00:54:50,052
- Everything we called worked.

1226
00:54:50,052 --> 00:54:52,908
- [Announcer] He's got Sanders
in the clear at the ten.

1227
00:54:52,908 --> 00:54:53,810
Touchdown!

1228
00:54:53,810 --> 00:54:55,176
Touchdown, Washington Redskins.

1229
00:54:55,176 --> 00:54:56,122
(crowd roaring)

1230
00:54:56,122 --> 00:54:58,372
And a new Superbowl record.

1231
00:54:59,500 --> 00:55:01,518
- I remember him holding
that helmet up, (laughing)

1232
00:55:01,518 --> 00:55:05,224
when he scored 35 points
in the second quarter.

1233
00:55:05,224 --> 00:55:09,047
One of the greatest quarter of
a game in Superbowl history.

1234
00:55:09,047 --> 00:55:12,869
- [Announcer] Doug Williams,
the MVP of Superbowl XXII.

1235
00:55:12,869 --> 00:55:15,190
- [Narrator] Williams was
the first black quarterback

1236
00:55:15,190 --> 00:55:17,259
to start or win a Superbowl

1237
00:55:17,259 --> 00:55:20,513
and was crowned the game's
most valuable player.

1238
00:55:20,513 --> 00:55:23,033
- It was one of those
times that I raised my hat

1239
00:55:23,033 --> 00:55:25,217
and thinking to myself, you know,

1240
00:55:25,217 --> 00:55:27,768
I'd really like to tell
some people where to go

1241
00:55:27,768 --> 00:55:29,806
but it wasn't in my nature to do it.

1242
00:55:29,806 --> 00:55:33,849
(upbeat music)
(crowd cheering)

1243
00:55:33,849 --> 00:55:35,454
- [Narrator] As the '80s drew to a close,

1244
00:55:35,454 --> 00:55:39,370
Barry's lifestyle continued
to make headlines.

1245
00:55:39,370 --> 00:55:42,120
- At no time did I see any drugs,

1246
00:55:43,285 --> 00:55:47,382
use any drugs, or have any
knowledge of any drugs.

1247
00:55:47,382 --> 00:55:50,632
That little white powder is so powerful

1248
00:55:52,926 --> 00:55:56,118
it causes you to do things you
never thought you would do.

1249
00:55:56,118 --> 00:55:59,805
- [Narrator] The FBI uncovered
more allegations of drug use

1250
00:55:59,805 --> 00:56:03,028
and rampant corruption
among Barry's staff,

1251
00:56:03,028 --> 00:56:06,209
and that included deputy
mayor Ivanhoe Donaldson.

1252
00:56:06,209 --> 00:56:09,626
- I have been tried, convicted, sentenced

1253
00:56:11,134 --> 00:56:14,987
and doing time by some
members of the media.

1254
00:56:14,987 --> 00:56:16,185
- [Woman] I think Marion was very good

1255
00:56:16,185 --> 00:56:18,033
about playing the victim.

